1
00:00:00,680 --> 00:00:05,779
The Mcginley Dynamic is a little-known yet
highly reliable indicator invented by John

2
00:00:05,779 --> 00:00:09,260
Mcginley, a certified market technician.

3
00:00:09,260 --> 00:00:15,170
Working within the context of moving averages,
Mcginley sought to invent a responsive indicator

4
00:00:15,170 --> 00:00:19,190
that would adjust itself in relation to the
speed of the market.

5
00:00:19,190 --> 00:00:22,650
The indicator itself resembles a lot like
a moving average.

6
00:00:22,650 --> 00:00:27,560
Well, Mcginley found that moving averages
had many problems.

7
00:00:27,560 --> 00:00:31,430
In the first place, they were inappropriately
applied.

8
00:00:31,430 --> 00:00:36,350
Moving averages in different periods operate
with varying degrees in different markets.

9
00:00:36,350 --> 00:00:42,130
For example, how to know when to use a 10-day,
20-day, or a 50-day moving average in a fast

10
00:00:42,130 --> 00:00:43,820
or slow market?

11
00:00:43,820 --> 00:00:48,100
In order to solve the problem of choosing
the right length of the moving average, the

12
00:00:48,100 --> 00:00:53,149
Mcginley Dynamic was built to automatically
adjust to the current speed of the market.

13
00:00:53,149 --> 00:00:58,561
Mcginley believes moving averages should only
be used as a smoothing mechanism rather than

14
00:00:58,561 --> 00:01:00,300
a trading system or signal generator.

15
00:01:00,300 --> 00:01:01,300
It is a monitor of trends.

16
00:01:01,300 --> 00:01:07,410
Further, Mcginley found moving averages failed
to follow prices since large separations frequently

17
00:01:07,410 --> 00:01:10,660
exist between prices and moving average lines.

18
00:01:10,660 --> 00:01:16,710
He sought to eliminate these problems by inventing
an indicator that would hug prices more closely,

19
00:01:16,710 --> 00:01:24,560
avoid price separation and whipsaws, and follow
prices automatically in fast or slow markets.

20
00:01:24,560 --> 00:01:30,180
The Mcginley Dynamic looks like a moving average
line, yet it is actually a smoothing mechanism

21
00:01:30,180 --> 00:01:35,009
for prices, and tracks prices far better than
any moving average.

22
00:01:35,009 --> 00:01:41,080
Because of its calculation, the dynamic line
speeds up in down markets as it follows prices

23
00:01:41,080 --> 00:01:44,159
yet moves more slowly in up markets.

24
00:01:44,159 --> 00:01:49,869
The key principle with this indicator is that
you would want to be quick to sell in a down

25
00:01:49,869 --> 00:01:54,119
market, yet ride an up market as long as possible.

26
00:01:54,119 --> 00:02:00,730
It greatly avoids whipsaws because the dynamic
line automatically follows and stays aligned

27
00:02:00,730 --> 00:02:06,229
to prices in any market—fast or slow—like
a steering mechanism of a car.

28
00:02:06,229 --> 00:02:12,489
That why traders can rely on it to make decisions
and time entrances and exits.

29
00:02:12,489 --> 00:02:18,959
Mcginley invented the dynamic to act as a
market tool rather than as a trading indicator.

30
00:02:18,959 --> 00:02:24,340
But whatever it's used for, the Mcginley Dynamic
is quite a fascinating instrument that is

31
00:02:24,340 --> 00:02:30,129
more responsive to the raw data than simple
or exponential moving averages.

32
00:02:30,129 --> 00:02:36,519
It aims to solve the problem inherent in all
moving averages — their reliance on fixed

33
00:02:36,519 --> 00:02:38,029
time periods.

34
00:02:38,029 --> 00:02:44,480
Here’s the logic behind this indicator:
in order to understand why Mcginley Dynamic

35
00:02:44,480 --> 00:02:48,980
is so special, let’s first take a look at
how conventional moving averages operate.

36
00:02:48,980 --> 00:02:57,940
A 10-period simple moving average takes 10
last closing prices and divides them by 10.

37
00:02:57,940 --> 00:03:00,859
A 20-period SMA will do the same but with
20.

38
00:03:00,859 --> 00:03:04,569
Old and new results receive the exact same
treatment.

39
00:03:04,569 --> 00:03:11,299
An EMA works in a similar fashion but allocates
more weight to recent results, which makes

40
00:03:11,299 --> 00:03:14,469
it perfectly suited for short-term trading.

41
00:03:14,469 --> 00:03:19,339
But how do you know when to use a 10-, 20-
or 50-period moving average?

42
00:03:19,339 --> 00:03:24,980
Mcginley Dynamic aims to solve this problem
as it will automatically adjust itself to

43
00:03:24,980 --> 00:03:26,930
slow and fast markets.

44
00:03:26,930 --> 00:03:32,729
While moving averages tend to lag behind the
actual price performance, displaying dated

45
00:03:32,729 --> 00:03:38,329
information most of the times, Mcginley Dynamic
will follow the prices more closely.

46
00:03:38,329 --> 00:03:43,769
You can think of Mcginley Dynamic as a better
version of a SMA or an EMA.

47
00:03:43,769 --> 00:03:48,370
So let’s compare this tool with a simple
moving average.

48
00:03:48,370 --> 00:03:54,869
We added the Mcginley Dynamic with a 20 period
input and a 20 period simple moving average.

49
00:03:54,869 --> 00:04:01,519
The Mcginley Dynamic reacts to price increases
sooner that the simple moving average whilst

50
00:04:01,519 --> 00:04:05,859
also tracking closer to prices and reducing
whipsaws.

51
00:04:05,859 --> 00:04:11,339
You can see that Mcginley moves faster in
bearish markets and slower in bullish markets

52
00:04:11,339 --> 00:04:16,459
(in order to give the market a chance to develop
necessary dynamics).

53
00:04:16,459 --> 00:04:22,580
Now that you know about the differences between
the moving averages and Mcginley dynamic,

54
00:04:22,580 --> 00:04:27,889
we can take a look at the 3 ways this tool
can be used to help you find trades, ride

55
00:04:27,889 --> 00:04:31,340
trends and exit trades in a reliable way.

56
00:04:31,340 --> 00:04:35,960
First approach, trend direction and filter.

57
00:04:35,960 --> 00:04:40,210
Similar to a moving average approach, you
can use the Mcginley Dynamic to stay on the

58
00:04:40,210 --> 00:04:45,169
right side of the market and to filter out
trades in the wrong direction.

59
00:04:45,169 --> 00:04:49,590
Just this one tip can already make a huge
difference in your trading when you only start

60
00:04:49,590 --> 00:04:52,710
trading with the trend in the right direction.

61
00:04:52,710 --> 00:04:58,289
Mcginley Dynamic will help you to cut down
the amount of "noise" on a price chart.

62
00:04:58,289 --> 00:05:03,771
Look at the direction of the dynamic line
to get a basic idea of which way the price

63
00:05:03,771 --> 00:05:05,229
is moving.

64
00:05:05,229 --> 00:05:11,610
If it is angled up, the price is moving up
(or was recently) overall; angled down, and

65
00:05:11,610 --> 00:05:18,360
the price is moving down overall; moving sideways,
and the price is likely in a range.

66
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:23,470
As a general guideline, if the price is above
the dynamic line, the trend is up.

67
00:05:23,470 --> 00:05:27,110
If the price is below it, the trend is down.

68
00:05:27,110 --> 00:05:29,860
As always, keep an eye on price action.

69
00:05:29,860 --> 00:05:35,530
Try to read the market and make trading decisions
based on the recent and actual price movements,

70
00:05:35,530 --> 00:05:38,250
rather than relying solely on this tool.

71
00:05:38,250 --> 00:05:42,300
You will have better results when you blend
this indicator into price action.

72
00:05:42,300 --> 00:06:03,340
Here are a few examples of trending markets,
using the Mcginley Dynamic.

73
00:06:03,340 --> 00:06:08,580
The second thing the dynamic line can help
you with is support and resistance trading

74
00:06:08,580 --> 00:06:11,509
and also stop placement.

75
00:06:11,509 --> 00:06:16,530
Because of the self-fulfilling prophecy, you
can often see that the popular moving averages

76
00:06:16,530 --> 00:06:20,240
work perfectly as support and resistance levels.

77
00:06:20,240 --> 00:06:26,800
Because the Mcginley Dynamic is basically
a moving average and because more than anything,

78
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:31,790
moving averages “work” because they are
a self-fulfilling prophecy, this means that

79
00:06:31,790 --> 00:06:37,930
price action respects moving averages because
so many traders use them in their own trading.

80
00:06:37,930 --> 00:06:43,879
This raises a very important point: you have
to stick to the most commonly used moving

81
00:06:43,879 --> 00:06:46,960
averages to get the best results.

82
00:06:46,960 --> 00:06:51,879
Moving averages work when a lot of traders
use and act on their signals.

83
00:06:51,879 --> 00:07:00,379
Thus, go with the crowd and only use the popular
periods (like 10, 20, 50,100 and 200).

84
00:07:00,379 --> 00:07:06,800
As its name suggests, this indicator may be
used as dynamic areas of support and resistance.

85
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:08,090
One importane note.

86
00:07:08,090 --> 00:07:14,490
The dynamic line is not perfect, and you can
see that many a times the price may go past

87
00:07:14,490 --> 00:07:17,300
it before moving back into the main trend.

88
00:07:17,300 --> 00:07:23,479
And, there’s no getting around this – it’s
best to think of Mcginley Dynamic as an area

89
00:07:23,479 --> 00:07:28,949
rather than precise point, and as always,
to have a stop loss in place.

90
00:07:28,949 --> 00:07:35,060
In fact, you can keep yourself reminded of
this by using two Mcginley Dynamic instead

91
00:07:35,060 --> 00:07:42,759
of just one, and use the area bounded between
these two lines as a zone of supply (support)

92
00:07:42,759 --> 00:07:47,090
or resistance as the case may be.

93
00:07:47,090 --> 00:07:51,870
Dynamic support and resistance can be found
where the dynamic line intersects with the

94
00:07:51,870 --> 00:07:53,199
current price.

95
00:07:53,199 --> 00:07:56,050
Let’s take a look at this Aussie Dollar
chart.

96
00:07:56,050 --> 00:08:02,400
We’ll look for dynamic support and resistance
supplied by the 10 and 20 dynamic lines.

97
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:07,289
Notice how the 10 and 20 dynamic lines appear
to be providing support and resistance.

98
00:08:07,289 --> 00:08:13,529
These two lines can be powerful aids, but
only used in combination with the right confluence

99
00:08:13,529 --> 00:08:14,529
factors.

100
00:08:14,529 --> 00:08:21,120
Let’s look at a setup where these dynamic
lines converge with several other factors.

101
00:08:21,120 --> 00:08:27,340
Notice how the pin bar in the chart above
rejected the 10-period Mcginley Dynamic and

102
00:08:27,340 --> 00:08:31,229
at the same time rejected a key price action
level?

103
00:08:31,229 --> 00:08:36,370
We also have an uptrend and no immediate resistance
above this key level.

104
00:08:36,370 --> 00:08:38,370
This was an “a+” setup.

105
00:08:38,370 --> 00:08:44,740
Take note that the 10-period Mcginley Dynamic
was only a fraction of why this was an A+

106
00:08:44,740 --> 00:08:45,740
setup.

107
00:08:45,740 --> 00:08:50,230
Like I said before, price action first, complemented
by this tool.

108
00:08:50,230 --> 00:09:15,220
Here are other examples of trades using Mcginley
Dynamic as a dynamic support and resistance.

109
00:09:15,220 --> 00:09:21,279
The Mcginley Dynamic tool is only as useful
as the other confluence factors that are present

110
00:09:21,279 --> 00:09:23,380
on any given trade setup.

111
00:09:23,380 --> 00:09:29,160
Although it offers several advantages over
classic moving averages, at its core is still

112
00:09:29,160 --> 00:09:33,260
a lagging indicator, because it’s based
on previous price action.

113
00:09:33,260 --> 00:09:37,250
The only thing that isn’t lagging is raw
price action.

114
00:09:37,250 --> 00:09:42,470
But this is okay because we can use this useful
tool as an additional confluence factor to

115
00:09:42,470 --> 00:09:45,240
our price action trading strategies.

116
00:09:45,240 --> 00:09:48,130
Which period for the Mcginley Dynamic should
you use?

117
00:09:48,130 --> 00:09:49,560
The answer is subjective.

118
00:09:49,560 --> 00:09:52,740
There’s no “right” way to use this indicator.

119
00:09:52,740 --> 00:09:58,130
Every trader seems to have their own combination
of periods that works best for them.

120
00:09:58,130 --> 00:10:02,670
I personally use the 50 and 200 Mcginley Dynamic
should.

121
00:10:02,670 --> 00:10:07,000
I have found them to work best with the way
i trade price action.

122
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:12,130
You can backtest different periods and add
this tool into your trading systems, to fit

123
00:10:12,130 --> 00:10:14,149
your trading style.

124
